english:
  title: A Lament on the Night Rain at Mapo
  author: Sung Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A patch of black cloud hangs low upon the sky,
    When echoes come—a solitary crane's cry from distant shores.
    With nightfall, south wind sweeps the ferry crossing wild,
    Stirring up the west river waters into flying rain.

    Fish dart and vanish, gaping mouths churning the depths,
    While Fengyi drums the waves and spirits dance in glee.
    The tumult sweeps across the islands into chaos and fog,
    Cool wind through the halls steals away the lingering heat.

    River geese scatter, crying out in confused refrain,
    Lotuseaves scatter too, tumbling with each tide.
    The fisherman shouts out, his anchor rope now lost,
    Great boats tilt and lean while small vessels drift away.

    What place in all this life is not fraught with danger?
    In but a moment, our days may fall to misfortune.
    Laughing at this scene, I, Ranggan, a humble scholar,
    Lie sleepless through the night, my head askew like a crane's.
  footnotes:
    - Fengyi (馮夷) is the ancient Chinese god of rivers, often depicted as stirring the waters and commanding the tides.
    - Ranggan (朗幹) is likely the poet's pen name or literary sobriquet, mentioned as a self-reference in the final stanza.
    - The poem uses the storm scene at Mapo, a historically significant ferry crossing on the Han River, as a meditation on life's unpredictability and the transience of human existence.
